      "component": "article",
      "metadata": {
        "source": "github.readme"
      },
      "html": "\n<p>There was a time, when Twitter changed its API and a lot of plug ins stopped working. At this time I just wanted to display my latest tweet on my own website, but without all that Twitter branded clutter. So, I decided to write my own server sided plug in.</p>\n<p>If you want to display your latest tweet with a specified #hashtag on a website, then this could maybe interesting for you!</p>\n<h3>Installation</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Head over to <a href=\"https://dev.twitter.com\">Twitter Developers</a>.</li>\n<li>Register yourself as developer and register a new app.</li>\n<li>Look for a safe directory on your server (e.g. <code>/bin</code>).</li>\n<li>Clone this repository into that directory.</li>\n<li>Make sure you have <a href=\"https://twython.readthedocs.org/en/latest/usage/install.html\">Twython</a> installed</li>\n<li>Open <code>config.json</code> set the parameters and save as <code>.config.json</code>.</li>\n<li>Setup a cronjob, which continously runs the script e.g. <code>*/10 * * * * PATH_TO_YOUR_SCRIPT/latestTweet.py</code>.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Dependencies</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://twython.readthedocs.org/en/latest/usage/install.html\">Twython</a> - Actively maintained, pure Python wrapper for the Twitter API.</li>\n</ul>\n"
